      <text xml:lang="en">
            <body>
                  <div type="article">
                        <head><title type="main"><rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">A
                                                Female Robinson
                              Crusoe</persName></rs>.</title></head>
                        <div n="1" type="section">
                              <p><span type="trope" n="3"><title type="article"
                                                key="#Hardacre1880_SM"
                                                ><emph>Scribner's</emph></title> has a wonderfully
                                          romantic story of an occurrence which happened on
                                                  <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_chi">the
                                                  Santa Barbara islands</placeName></rs>, a cluster
                                          off <rs><placeName type="region" key="#re_paccoast">the
                                                  California coast</placeName></rs>, which, in
                                                  <rs><date notBefore="1400" notAfter="1499-12-31"
                                                  >the fifteenth century</date></rs>, were densely
                                          peopled by <rs><orgName type="group"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva; #natam_GabrilenoTongva; #natam_chumash"
                                                  >a superior race</orgName></rs>, described as
                                          white, with light hair and ruddy cheeks, the women with
                                          fine forms, beautiful eyes and modest demeanor, who
                                          dressed in petticoats and capes of sealskin, embroidered
                                          with pearl and small pink shells.</span>
                                    <span type="trope" n="6">But in time <rs><orgName
                                                  type="nativeamericantribes"
                                                  key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">the
                                                  inhabitants</orgName></rs> mysteriously melted
                                          away, and in <date when="1835">1835</date>
                                          <rs><name type="ship" key="#sh_peoresnada">a
                                                  schooner</name></rs> was sent to bring <persName
                                                type="group" key="#bhagroup">the remnant</persName>
                                          to <placeName type="region" key="#re_mld">the main
                                                land</placeName>.</span> After <rs><name type="ship"
                                                key="#sh_peoresnada">the ship</name></rs> had
                                    sailed, it was found that <rs><persName type="nativeamerican"
                                                key="#lwchild">a child</persName></rs> had been left
                                    behind, <rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">the
                                                mother</persName></rs> supposing it to have been
                                    carried aboard by <rs><persName type="group"
                                                key="#1835crew; #chu; #isp; #iwi; #jsjo; #jdy; #lbu; #natam_hawaiian; #nativeamericans"
                                                >an old sailor</persName></rs>. She frantically
                                    implored <rs><persName type="group" key="#chu; #isp">the
                                                captain</persName></rs> to return, but, a storm
                                    threatening, he refused. <span type="trope" n="9">She became
                                          desperate, and jumping overboard swam for the
                                          shore.</span> No attempt was made to rescue her, and the
                                                <rs><persName type="group" key="#chu; #isp">captain
                                                of the schooner</persName></rs>, although promising
                                    to visit <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">the
                                                island</placeName></rs> and take her off, never did
                                    so, his <rs><name type="ship" key="#sh_peoresnada"
                                          >vessel</name></rs> shortly after being destroyed in a
                                    storm. <span type="trope" n="12">There being no other sea craft
                                          on <rs><placeName type="region" key="#re_socalcoast">that
                                                  coast</placeName></rs>, and no one caring to
                                          attempt a passage of seventy miles in an open boat, the
                                          event faded out of interest and finally out of memory
                                          until <rs><date when="1850">fifteen years
                                                afterward</date></rs>, when, under the promise of
                                          $200, <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">the
                                                  island</placeName></rs> was visited and searched,
                                          but with no results.</span>
                                    <span type="trope" n="3">The attempt, however, revived the
                                          story, and <rs><date when="1853">three years
                                                  afterward</date></rs>
                                          <persName type="frontiersman" key="#gni">a
                                                captain</persName> and <rs><persName type="group"
                                                  key="#cdi; #col; #msh; #poli; #nsk; #hva">crew of
                                                  otter-hunters</persName></rs>, walking along the
                                          beach in "one of those limpid nights of which <placeName
                                                type="state" key="#st_cal">California</placeName>
                                          knows" saw on the lonely shore the print of a slender
                                          naked foot. Search was begun, and after several days'
                                          march a dangerous climb brought <rs><persName
                                                  type="frontiersman" key="#cdi"
                                                >Brown</persName></rs>, <rs><persName
                                                  type="frontiersman" key="#cdi">the
                                                  captain</persName></rs>, to a spot where there
                                          were fresh footprints, which he followed up the cliffs
                                          until they were lost in the thick moss. Then his eyes
                                          caught a small object a long way off on the hills. It
                                          appeared like a crow at first glance, but advancing
                                          steadily he found it was the head of a woman barely
                                          visible above the low-woven brush sides of her roofless
                                          retreat in the bushes.</span> Her complexion was much
                                    fairer than the ordinary Indian, and she had regular features,
                                    and thick brown hair, which fell about her shoulders in a
                                    tangled mat. She was talking to herself and watching with alarm
                                                <rs><persName type="group"
                                                key="#gni; #col; #cook; #msh; #poli; #nsk; #hva"
                                                >Brown's companions</persName></rs> on the plat
                                    below. When he stepped forward and spoke to her she ran a few
                                    steps, then, controlling herself, stopped and answered him in an
                                    unknown tongue. <span type="trope" n="1">She was dressed in a
                                          tunic-shaped garment made of birds' plumage, low in the
                                          neck, sleeveless, and reaching to the ankle. She greeted
                                          them all with a simple dignity, and set about preparing
                                          food for them.</span>
                                    <span type="trope" n="10">They made her understand by signs that
                                          she was to go with them, and she gladly did so. By signs
                                          she, on her part, told her history. She had never found
                                                  <rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lwchild"
                                                  >her child</persName></rs>, which was probably
                                          destroyed by the wild dogs of the <rs><placeName
                                                  type="island" key="#i_sn">the
                                                island</placeName></rs>. She made a fire by rubbing
                                          sticks together, and for <rs><date from="1835" to="1853"
                                                  >eighteen years</date></rs> had kept it alight
                                          like a vestal flame, and had lived on roots, fish, seals'
                                          blubber and shell-fish.</span>
                                    <span type="trope" n="3"><span type="trope" n="6">Her return to
                                                the confining and unhealthful conditions of
                                                civilization after her free out-door life soon
                                                killed her. The story, of which this is only a brief
                                                sketch, is wonderfully fascinating from beginning to
                                                end.</span></span></p>
                        </div>
                  </div>
